eory of Gases</i> (1927), p. 14.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-30" id="cite_note-30"><a href="./Heat#cite_ref-30" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-30" class="mw-reference-text">From this terminological choice may derive a tradition to the effect that the letter <i id="mwAkQ">Q</i> represents "quantity", but there is no indication that Clausius had this in mind when he selected the letter in what seemed to be an <i id="mwAkU">ad hoc</i> calculation in 1850.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-31" id="cite_note-31"><a href="./Heat#cite_ref-31" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-31" class="mw-reference-text">B.L. Loeb, <i id="mwAkY">The Kinetic Theory of Gases</i> (1927), <a rel="mw:ExtLink" class="external text" href="https://books.google.ch/books?id=KNh0PFk7CnwC&amp;pg=PA426" id="mwAkc">p. 426</a>.</span></li><li about="#cite_note-Carathéodory_1909-32" id="cite_note-Carathéodory_1909-32"><span rel="mw:referencedBy"><a href="./Heat#cite_ref-Carathéodory_1909_32-0"><span class="mw-linkback-text">1 </span></a><a href="./Heat#cite_ref-Carathéodory_1909_32-1"><span class="mw-linkback-text">2 </span></a></span> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-Carathéodory_1909-32" class="mw-reference-text"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Constantin_Carathéodory" title="Constantin Carathéodory" id="mwAkg">Carathéodory, C.</a> (1909).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-33" id="cite_note-33"><a href="./Heat#cite_ref-33" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-33" class="mw-reference-text">Adkins, C.J. (1968/1983).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-34" id="cite_note-34"><a href="./Heat#cite_ref-34" rel="mw:referencedBy"><span class="mw-linkback-text">↑ </span></a> <span id="mw-reference-text-cite_note-34" class="mw-reference-text">Münster, A. (1970).</span></li><li about="#cite_note-35" id=